<DOC><DOCNO> AP880325-0301 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-25-88 2236EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f AM-PacificEnterprises     03-25 0265</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Pacific Enterprises,0275</SECOND><HEAD>Pacific Enterprises to Buy More Texas Oil, Gas Properties</HEAD><DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   In its second foray into the Texas oil andgas market this month, Pacific Enterprises said Friday it hasagreed to buy Sabine Corp. of Dallas for $24 per share, or $339million.   That is a 20 percent premium over the $20 per share at whichSabine's stock closed Thursday. In the past year, its stock hastraded as high as $20.75 per share and as low as $9.37{.   The deal, which is contingent upon 75 percent of the company'sshares being tendered, has been approved unanimously by Sabine'sdirectors, the companies said.   As part of the agreement, Pacific Enterprises received an optionto buy 2.6 million shares, or 18{ percent, for $24 per share.   Sabine is engaged in exploration, development and acquisition ofcrude oil and natural gas in the United States.   Pacific Enterprises, which until recently was known as PacificLighting Corp., is the parent of Southern California Gas Co. Italso has gas and oil exploration and pipeline operations and runsdrugstore and sporting goods chains.   The deal will give Pacific Enterprises proved oil and gasreserves equivalent to 32 million barrels of oil, plus $55 millionin cash and mineral rights and leaseholds to nearly 4 million acresof land.   It will boost Pacific Enterprises' proved reserves by 36 percent.   Earlier this month, the company agreed to buy half the oil andgas mineral rights under 70,000 acres in Texas for $93 million.That acreage is on the Burnett Ranch in King County, Texas.</TEXT></DOC>